            <h2>Angeles City</h2>

            <img src="<?= $this->webroot ?>theme/weatherph/img/tourism/angelesCity1.png" alt="Angeles City">

            <p>Angeles City is a highly urbanized city located in the province of Pampanga. Economic growth for this City was initially perceived as an offshoot of the presence of the adjacent Clark Air Base but the eruption of Mt. Pinatubo in 1991 and the subsequent evacuation of the Americans proved this wrong. The resilience of the Angelenos, however, rose above this tragedy.</p>
            <p>Tourism in the City has become a flourishing industry with the influx of travelers comprising mostly of long staying guests. Life- style comforts are within reach but the City maintains a relaxed atmosphere that is usually enjoyed in the countryside.</p>
            <p>With its growing number of foreign residents who have brought their culture with them, the City pulsates with a cosmopolitan vibe.</p>
            <p>Angelenos are recognized for their skills, knowledge and appreciation of excellent food. Angeles City is a melting pot of cultures where one can enjoy the best of Kapampangan cooking along- side high quality international cuisine.</p>

            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>1. Tigtigan Terakan Keng Dalan Festival is Kapampangan for music and dancing in the streets. Every year on the last Friday and Saturday nights of October, the City holds the biggest street party that can last until the break of dawn. Started in 1991, it was conceptualized to uplift the spirit of the city residents from the devastated impact of Mt. Pinatubo. Now on its 20th year, the event lives on to commemorate Angeleno resilience and celebrate life after the tragedy of the Mt. Pinatubo eruption.</li>
                <li>2. La Naval Fiesta, the first of Angeles City’s twin fiesta in October, is held every second Sunday in commemoration of the Virgin of the Holy Rosary, whose intercession saw the victory of the Spanish fleet over the Dutch invaders. The City celebrates fiesta with traditional religious programs while homes display the finest traditions of hospitality by entertaining guests with their best cooking and most extravagant food spread.</li>
                <li>3. Piyesta ning Apung Mamacalulu or the Feast of Our Lord of Mercy, the second of the twin fiesta, is celebrated on the last Friday of October. Devotees from all over Pampanga flock to the Apu shrine every Friday to venerate the miraculous image of Jesus Christ lying in the sepulcher.</li>
                <li>4. Philippine Independence Day Re-Enactment at the Old Pamintuan Mansion is performed on June 12 every year. In 1899, a year after the independence of the Philippines under Spanish rule, President Emilio Aguinaldo moved the seat of government to Angeles City during the Filipino-American War. A passionate re-enactment of the first and only Independence Day anniversary celebration is held yearly complete with the actual speech of Aguinaldo translated into Filipino.</li>
                <li>5. Limbun is a Good Friday procession featuring circa 1830 religious carriages and iconic floats. Since the early 1800s, this Lenten tradition is attended by devotees and visitors including men who wear traditional costumes while pulling the carros which adds color to the serene proceedings.</li>
            </ol>

